{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "Test Coverage Gap Report",
  "description": "After a task completes, analyze the test suite against ALL production JS code under js/ to report coverage metrics and write a timestamped markdown report to tests/reports/. Deletes older reports before writing the new one.",
  "version": "3",
  "when": {
    "type": "agentStop"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "After this task completed, generate a Test Coverage Gap Report. Do the following:\n\n1. Scan ALL production JS/MJS files under js/ recursively (including all subdirectories).\n2. Scan ALL test spec files under tests/ recursively (including all subdirectories).\n3. For each production file, identify all exported/defined functions and methods.\n4. Cross-reference against the test files to determine which functions have test coverage.\n5. Compute approximate coverage metrics:\n   - % of files with at least one corresponding test file\n   - % of functions/methods that have at least one test\n   - Estimate branch coverage based on conditional logic tested vs untested\n6. Delete any existing coverage-gap-report*.md files in tests/reports/ to clean up old reports.\n7. Write the full report as a markdown file to tests/reports/coverage-gap-report.<MM-dd-HH-mm>.md where the timestamp uses the current date/time (month-day-hour-minute). Create the directory if needed. The markdown report should include:\n   - Header with date/time\n   - Summary metrics section (use ✅ if >= 90%, ⚠️ if 70-89%, 🔴 if < 70%)\n   - Fully Untested section (table with columns: File | Function | Reason Not Tested)\n   - Partially Tested section (table with columns: File | Function | What's Missing)\n   - Recommendations section with brief suggestions on how to add coverage\n\nDo NOT print the report contents to the session. Only confirm that the report file was written and state the filename."
  }
}
